Umbrella Corporation AR-15 Bolt Carrier Groups are our take on a premium, no snake oil, combat ready BCG. Each and every bolt is proof fired, ultrasonically cleaned, tested via magnetic particle inspection (MPI), and once certified, parkerized for corrosion protection and lube retention. In keeping with a superior product, we don't utilize a Crane O-Ring as a crutch to increase extractor tension. Instead, our bolts are built with a mil-spec black insert coupled with a Tactical Springs 5-coil high load extractor spring that's compatible with all DI gas system lengths. It's rated for 150K+ cycles to outlast your rifle barrel many times over. We have improved on the finish requirement of the TDP and have chosen the best materials of those allowed per spec, not the lowest cost like nearly all of our competitors. This second gen product is manufactured to the highest standards with an unconditional guarantee against material defect and manufacturing failure. We challenge you to compare our Bolt Carrier Group specs against the competition. Beyond using Carpenter's 158 alloy for the bolt, ask what alloy they use for their extractors, Extractor pins, ejectors, and whether their cam pins have a solid film lube per TDP. You will likely find they don't advertise any of these specifications.  And don't fall for the 9310 alloy bolt substitute; it is a less expensive, inferior alloy for this application. Bought into the hype and don't believe us? Ask Carpenter Tech; they manufacture both materials and will without hesitation tell you 158 is the proper, superior alloy. The draw for 9310 is that it's a decent material when heat treated properly though since there's no spec, how do you know what "proper" might be for this application? It's less costly, and you don't have to buy mill run quantities for manufacturing. It's the little things that make the real difference and we cut no corners with our Bolt Carrier Groups. as before, this initial first release is offered with a discount below our suggested retail pricing. Assembly/function check by a qualified Armorer is required.

Specifications

Extractor Retaining Pin, precision machined and ground S2 shock resistant tool steel alloy per ASTM A681-08 (vs typical S7; mil-spec allows S1 to S7), heat treated per ASTM A681-08, shot peened per mil-spec print, manganese phosphate
Extractor Spring (premium spring eliminates need for Crane O-Ring), Tactical Springs/Sprinco 5 coil, ASTM Grade A401 Chrome Silicon wire stock, heat treated, stress relieved, Molybdenum-Disulfide infused, cryogenic processed (all post winding), mil-spec black insert/synthetic elastomer extractor buffer (nitrile-butadiene, shore hardness 80+/-5 durometer per MIL-PRF-6855)

Gas Rings, mil standard stainless steel X3
Carrier machined from AISI 8620 aircraft qualty alloy per ASTM A108/A322-13, full auto profile, surface finish improved over mil-spec, heat treated (carburized/strain relieved per mil-spec print), hard chrome bore, precision ground gas key interface, Umbrella logo deep laser engraved, manganese phosphate
Gas Key machined from 4130 chromoly steel alloy per ASTM A108/A322-13, heat treated, hard chrome internal, manganese phosphate, Permatex sealed, Grade 8 Torx Plus cap screws torqued and staked all per mil-spec
Cam Pin—precision machined 4340 chromoly steel alloy per SAE AMS6415T/AMS6484D, heat treated/processed per mil-spec, manganese phosphate, solid film lubricant applied and cured per mil-spec

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1873 Rifle, 32-20, 32 WCF, 1887 Vintage, 24" Octagon Barrel, Good Shooter!
postcontent: UPDATE: Go to the following link to see recent YouTube videos of this gun in action and of the bore. The first 3 videos listed are the most recent.https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCHJBTeUlWPDGszT21zEOL6QWinchester 1873 Rifle. Caliber 32-20 also known as 32WCF. 1887 Vintage. Has a 24" Octagon Barrel. This is a good shooter and I would consider it to be in good condition overall. We were just at the range the other day and fired off 25 rounds with it. Still have about 25 rounds remaining that will go with it. This is a joint venture between my uncle and I and it used to be his late brother's (my other uncle) who was an avid gun collector. I have done all the work on it this past year. It probably sat for 40-50 years prior to that!Condition: I admittedly do not know how to grade antique guns so i will describe to the best of my ability. The wood is real nice with most varnish remaining with a few dings here and there. The front stock is very slightly loose. The "blueing", which is actually plum brown, is very good on the barrel with minor pitting and fair/good on the rest of the parts with more pitting except for the magazine tube which is missing blueing. The side plates and front stock end cap are nickle-plated and slightly pitted. Internally, the toggles are fine and do not look to have ever been without lube as well as the rest of the internals. The firing pin/bolt may have seen some work at one point in time but not from me. There were parts missing that have been replaced by me such as the magazine follower, spring and end cap as well as the mainspring tension screw. Those were new reproduction parts from homesteadpartsdotcom. There still might need to be a little bit of fine-tuning done to the action as it is a little stiff but it fired fine at the range.The screw-in octagon barrel was loose and a little over-clocked (about 5 degrees) when I tried to tighten it so I created some shims to get it to line up correctly when tightened. I ended up at .0015" or so. The bore is pitted but the rifling is certainly pronounced and the gun produced good groups at the range. Fired cases look fine with no evidence of headspace issues or bulging.I also repaired the magazine tube band that holds it to the barrel by milding reshaping the band dovetail and gently peening the barrel dovetail. This work is unnoticable and I was able to reuse the original roll pin. I'm pretty sure I bought a spare when I bought the other parts.Includes 25 rounds of 32-20 jacketed ammo and about the same number of empty cases. I think these can be reloaded with 32ACP bullets and small rifle primers (I think). Ammo is out there if you look and certainly at the gun shows.Looking for $1873 or serious cash offer or trade. Will consider interesting trades plus cash such as maybe a "newer" lever-action in .38 or .44 and/or possibly a small or large carry/hunting pistol/revolver and/or .22 pistol/revolver. No junk trades or low-ball offers, please!Will consider shipping with prepayment as this is an antique and will ship through the mail without FFL regulations. Even then, it IS legal for a private party to ship a long gun in-state to another private party. Credit Cards ARE accepted! Serious only contact me through the AL messaging system but please be patient for a reply. Be sure to leave a contact number and I'll get back to you in a day or so.

title: For Sale:  Rare Daisy No 105/7 Over Stamped Buck Jones BB Gun
postcontent:
The following information is from Gary Garber's "Encyclopedia of PLYMOUTH Guns." "In 1933, when Daisy began making the Buck Jones Special, they had some No. 105 frames left over from the Junior Pump Gun run. Being the kind of company that never wasted any materials, Daisy just stamped over the "5" with the number "7". Because the gun was aqlready stamped "Junior Pump Gun" it became the No. 107 Junior Pump Gun. This is, by far, the most difficult variation of the No. 107 Buck Jones to find."
Ok that is what I found out about this BB gun it is in good shape it does show normal ware for a BB gun of its age. It has a compass and stamped sundial on the butt and a little rust and ware on the barrel, there is a couple spots of paint that can be easily removed. It is stamped 105/7 on the barrel. Please cont me with any other questions or info for this great BB gun.
